--- &quot;Tambascio, Larry&quot; &lt;ltambascio@...&gt; wrote:

&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Hi Sreenivasa,
&gt; 
&gt; Cactus (http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus) is the closest you&#39;ll probably get
&gt; to an EJB testing framework.  The approach it takes is to run the tests from
&gt; it&#39;s own servlet, so you&#39;re running the test in the container.  It makes for
&gt; a good integration test (make sure it&#39;s deployed correctly, etc.).
&gt; Deploying to run tests may slow things down a little.
&gt; 
&gt; Another option would be mock objects (http://www.mockobjects.com,
&gt; http://www.easymock.org).  It has a lot of mock objects that will make your
&gt; EJB think it&#39;s in a container.  I actually haven&#39;t tried them for EJBs, but
&gt; it would be the first place I would go.
&gt; 
&gt; If your EJB is simply a faï¿½ade, then I&#39;d concentrate more on testing the
&gt; supporting business classes/methods, which it sounds like you&#39;re already
&gt; doing.
&gt; 
&gt; Good luck,
&gt; -Larry
